      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Order-of-accuracy tests performed on canonical pipe-flow and rotating-disk benchmarks confirm second-order spatial convergence for the pressure-velocity coupling scheme. Manufactured-solution verification for the scalar transport equation used in the hemolysis model confirms correct implementation. Results documented in the solver verification report VVR-2023-001.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/ncv-mrl2",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical code verification criterion for MRL 2",
        "description": "Demonstrated second-order spatial convergence on at least two canonical benchmarks relevant to the physics of interest. Manufactured-solution or exact-solution comparison required for any custom scalar transport implementation."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Richardson extrapolation performed on three systematically refined meshes (0.8 M, 3.2 M, 12.8 M hexahedral cells). GCI for the fine mesh is 2.1% for NIH and 1.4% for pressure head, both well below the 5% acceptance threshold. Observed order of convergence p = 1.94 confirms near-second-order behaviour. The medium mesh (3.2 M) was selected for production runs, yielding GCI_medium = 4.8% — within acceptance — with a factor-of-four reduction in compute time versus the fine mesh.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/disc-mrl2",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error criterion for MRL 2",
        "description": "GCI for the production mesh must be below 5% for all primary QoIs. Richardson extrapolation on a minimum of three mesh levels required. Achieved level 3 (GCI < 5% with systematic three-level study) exceeds the MRL 2 requirement of level 2."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, haematocrit) were controlled and recorded for all 45 validation measurements. Boundary conditions applied in the CFD model are directly matched to the measured test conditions. Deviations between nominal and measured conditions are within ±2% for flow rate and ±10 RPM for speed, which are within the experimental uncertainty bands.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/tc-mrl2",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions criterion for MRL 2",
        "description": "Experimental boundary conditions must be documented and directly mapped to CFD inlet/outlet conditions. Deviations between nominal and measured test conditions must be within the stated experimental uncertainty."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison of CFD-predicted NIH against experimental measurements using the validation metric E = (CFD - Exp) / Exp. All 45 comparisons fall within ±15% acceptance band. Statistical summary: mean E = +2.1%, standard deviation 3.8%, 95th percentile absolute error 8.7%. Comparison plots and tabulated data provided in validation report VVR-2023-002.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/oc-mrl2",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison criterion for MRL 2",
        "description": "All primary QoI comparisons must fall within ±15% of experimental measurements. A quantitative validation metric must be reported with statistical summary across all comparison points."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "The primary QoI (normalised index of hemolysis, NIH) and the derived decision metric (relative hemolysis index, RH) are both directly relevant to the COU decision of identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions. NIH is the standard hemolysis metric used in FDA guidance for CPB device evaluation. The mapping from NIH to the RH < 1 acceptance criterion is documented and clinically justified.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/rqi-mrl2",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance criterion for MRL 2",
        "description": "The QoIs used in validation must be the same quantities used in the COU decision, or a documented and justified mapping must exist. QoIs must align with regulatory guidance for the device class."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Validation activities were conducted using the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is the same device family as the COU device. Operating conditions span the full COU operating envelope (2–6 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). The blood analogue fluid (glycerol-water, matched viscosity) and haematocrit range (35–45%) are representative of CPB clinical conditions. Geometric similarity between validation and COU configurations is documented in the validation plan VP-2023-001.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/rva-mrl2",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation relevance criterion for MRL 2",
        "description": "Validation must be performed on a geometry within the same device family as the COU device. Operating conditions must span the COU envelope. Fluid properties must be representative of the clinical use conditions."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error (iterative convergence error) is scoped out at MRL 2 because the solver employs a coupled pressure-velocity algorithm with documented convergence criteria (residuals < 1e-6 for all equations, mass imbalance < 0.01%). These criteria are enforced automatically and verified by the SQA regression suite. Separate quantification of solver error beyond what is captured in the discretisation error assessment is not required at MRL 2 for this device class."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment is scoped out at MRL 2. The simulation workflow is executed by a single qualified analyst under a documented simulation protocol (SP-2023-CPB-001) with peer review of all boundary condition assignments and mesh generation steps. The risk of consequential use error is mitigated by the protocol controls and is not required to be separately quantified at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty (turbulence model selection, hemolysis constitutive law) is partially addressed within the sensitivity analysis (turbulence model switch contributes ±6% to RH) and the discretisation error budget. A separate model form uncertainty quantification is not required at MRL 2 for a Class II device with medium model influence, provided the sensitivity analysis captures the dominant model form contributors."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Formal model input uncertainty propagation (e.g. Monte Carlo or polynomial chaos) is scoped out at MRL 2. Key input sensitivities are characterised by the Morris screening sensitivity analysis, which identifies tip clearance and rotational speed as dominant inputs. The operating envelope bounds these inputs conservatively. Full probabilistic input uncertainty propagation is not required at MRL 2 for this device class and model risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test sample variability assessment (device-to-device manufacturing variation in the validation hardware) is scoped out at MRL 2. The FDA generic pump geometry is a single reference geometry with tightly controlled manufacturing tolerances (±0.05 mm on critical dimensions). Sample-to-sample variability is negligible relative to the parametric variations studied in the COU and is not required to be separately characterised at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters between the validation configuration and the COU configuration is addressed qualitatively through the relevance of validation activities assessment (factor above). A separate formal equivalency analysis is not required at MRL 2 given that the validation geometry is within the same device family and the operating conditions span the COU envelope. The documented geometric similarity and operating condition mapping in VP-2023-001 is sufficient at MRL 2."
